04172nam a22006255i 9780292703056DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212002txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927030567 a10.7560/7557892doi  a(DE-B1597)588281  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aPN1995.9.M27bN63 2002 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a791.43/6552221 aNochimson, Martha P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aScreen Couple Chemistry :bThe Power of 2 /cMartha P. Nochimson. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (408 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tOne An Introduction to the Importance of Couple Chemistry under the Studio System -- tTwo Johnny Weissmuller and Maureen O'Sullivan: Tarzan and Jane -- tThree Myrna Loy and William Powell: The Thin Man Takes a Couple -- tFour Fred Astaire and Ginger Rogers: MUSIC Makes Me -- tFive Katharine Hepburn and Spencer Tracy: Much Ado about "the Little Woman" -- tSix The Post-Studio Synergistic Couple: The Thin Aliens -- tSeven The Thematic Couple: A Post-Studio Innovation -- tAPPENDIX One Fred, Ginger, and RKO -- tAPPENDIX Two Theorizing Chemistry in Entertainment via Neuroscience -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAstaire and Rogers, Tracy and Hepburn. Just the mention of their names evokes the powerful chemistry between these screen couples, which utterly transcended the often formulaic films in which they appeared together. Indeed, watching the synergistic flow of energy between charismatic screen partners is one of the great pleasures of cinema and television, as well as an important vehicle for thinking through issues of intimacy and gender relations. In this book, Martha P. Nochimson engages in a groundbreaking study of screen couple chemistry. She begins by classifying various types of couples to define what sets the synergistic couple apart from other onscreen pairings. Then she moves into extended discussions of four enduring screen couples—Maureen O'Sullivan/Johnny Weissmuller, Myrna Loy/William Powell, Fred Astaire/Ginger Rogers, and Katharine Hepburn/Spencer Tracy. Using theories of neuroscience, she demonstrates that their onscreen chemistry is a very real phenomenon, powerful enough to subvert conventional formulations of male/female relations. Material she has uncovered in the infamous Production Code Administration files illuminates the historical context of her contentions. Finally, Nochimson traces the screen couple to its present-day incarnation in such pairs as Woody Allen/Diane Keaton, Scully/Mulder of The X-Files, and Cliff/Claire Huxtable of The Cosby Show.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aLove in motion pictures. 0aMan-woman relationships in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/75578940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292703056423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292703056/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK